# Forge project conventions — {{.Name}}

> **This file is forge-managed.** It is written once by `{{.CLI}} new` (and is not regenerated by `{{.CLI}} generate`). Do not hand-edit — changes will be lost if you re-scaffold. Put project-specific notes in the top-level `reliant.md` instead.

This is a **Forge** project — a Connect RPC development framework purpose-built for LLM-driven development. Proto is the canonical input format. Everything — API contracts, ORM code, middleware, mocks — is derived from proto definitions annotated with `forge.v1` extensions.

## Philosophy

- **Proto-first.** The contract lives in `proto/`. Go handlers, clients, and DTOs under `gen/` are all derived from it. If you want to change a message or RPC, change the proto and regenerate — never hand-edit `gen/`.
- **Everything is Connect RPC.** Services talk to each other (and to frontends) through the same interface pattern. There are no side-channel APIs.
- **Internal boundaries use Go interfaces.** For components that can't be expressed in proto (channels, complex types, factories), `{{.CLI}} package new <name>` creates an `internal/<name>/contract.go` with an interface contract, and codegen produces mocks and middleware from it.
- **Mockable by default.** Because every boundary — Connect or Go-interface — has generated mocks, tests can swap real implementations without rewiring anything.
- **Convention over configuration.** `{{.CLI}} new`, `{{.CLI}} add`, `{{.CLI}} package`, and the `Taskfile.yml` encode the project layout. Follow them and the CLI keeps working. Fight them and you're on your own.
- **LLM-optimized.** File layout, naming, and scaffolding are chosen so an agent can find things by pattern. Don't "cleverly" reorganize — you'll break the conventions other agents rely on.

## Architecture

Proto is the canonical input format with two lifecycles:

- **Scaffold** (runs once per entity): plan proto → full skeleton → plan proto deleted
- **Generate** (runs always): service protos → stubs, hooks, mocks (idempotent)

```
proto/services/<svc>/v1/   # Service definitions with forge.v1 annotations
  → protoc-gen-forge --mode=descriptor → forge_descriptor.json
  → protoc-gen-forge --mode=orm → ORM code (*.pb.orm.go)
  → protoc-gen-go + protoc-gen-connect-go → stubs

internal/*/contract.go     # Go interfaces (LLM-owned)
  → forge generate → mock_gen.go, middleware_gen.go, tracing_gen.go
```

### Proto annotations (forge.v1)

All annotations live in `forge/v1/forge.proto`:
- `forge.v1.entity` — on messages: table name, soft_delete, timestamps, indexes, middleware
- `forge.v1.field` — on fields: pk, tenant, store, ref, unique, index, validate, immutable
- `forge.v1.service` — on services: name, version, visibility, auth config
- `forge.v1.method` — on RPCs: auth_required, idempotent, timeout, idempotency_key
- `forge.v1.config` — on fields: env_var, flag, default_value, required, description

## Rules

- **Never hand-edit anything under `gen/`.** It's overwritten on every `{{.CLI}} generate`. Fix the `.proto` instead.
- **`gen/` is not committed.** Only `gen/go.mod` and `gen/go.sum` are tracked. Fresh clones must run `{{.CLI}} generate` before `{{.CLI}} run` or `{{.CLI}} test`.
- **Run `{{.CLI}} generate` after any proto change.** Stale generated code is the #1 source of mysterious compile errors.
- **Use `{{.CLI}} test`, not raw `go test`.** The CLI sets the right build tags (`integration`) that bare `go test` would skip.
- **Use `{{.CLI}} debug`, not raw `dlv`.** The CLI manages session state in `.forge/debug-session.json` so subsequent commands reconnect to the same session. Step commands are **`stepin`** / **`stepout`** (no hyphens).
- **All `{{.CLI}} db migrate ...` commands require `--dsn`.** Set `DATABASE_URL` once in your shell: `export DATABASE_URL="postgres://postgres:postgres@localhost:5432/{{.Name}}?sslmode=disable"`.
- **Migrations are append-only history.** Once merged, never edit a migration — write a new one.
- **Secrets never live in the repo.** Not in KCL, not in code, not in comments. Use cluster-level secret management.
- **`{{.CLI}} deploy` takes the environment as a positional arg**, not `--env`. Production deploys require explicitly typing `prod`.
- **`{{.CLI}} package new` creates internal Go packages, not Docker images.** Docker image builds live under `{{.CLI}} build --docker`.
- **Contract enforcement is strict by default.** Every `internal/` package with exported methods must have a `contract.go`. Configure exceptions in `forge.yaml` under `contracts.exclude`.

## What Forge generates (and what it doesn't)

| Forge generates (safe to regenerate) | You own (Forge never touches) |
|--------------------------------------|-------------------------------|
| `gen/` — Go stubs, TS clients, mocks | `handlers/<svc>/` — business logic |
| `pkg/app/bootstrap.go` — service wiring | `pkg/app/setup.go` — custom wiring |
| `pkg/middleware/` — HTTP/Connect middleware | `internal/db/` — entity types, ORM functions |
| Frontend hooks and Connect clients | `db/migrations/` — schema (source of truth) |
| Test harness, mock servers | `db/queries/` — SQL queries |
| CI/CD, Docker, deploy configs | `internal/<pkg>/` — internal packages |
| `forge_descriptor.json` — proto descriptor data | `internal/<pkg>/contract.go` — interface contracts |

Running `{{.CLI}} generate` is always safe. It regenerates infrastructure from proto definitions. It will never overwrite your handlers, DB layer, or business logic.

## Project layout

```
proto/services/<svc>/v1/   # Protobuf service definitions with forge.v1 annotations
gen/                       # Generated code — NEVER hand-edit, not committed
handlers/<svc>/            # Go handler implementations (your business logic)
frontends/<name>/          # Next.js frontends consuming generated TS clients
internal/db/               # Database layer: types.go, <entity>_orm.go (YOU own this)
internal/<name>/           # Internal Go packages with interface contracts
pkg/app/bootstrap.go       # Generated wiring — DO NOT EDIT (regenerated by forge generate)
pkg/app/setup.go           # User-editable hook for custom wiring (//forge:allow)
pkg/middleware/             # HTTP/Connect middleware (generated)
db/migrations/             # SQL migrations — schema source of truth (YOU own this)
db/queries/                # SQL query definitions
deploy/kcl/<env>/          # KCL deployment manifests per environment
e2e/                       # End-to-end tests (run against live stack)
forge.yaml                 # Project config: services, ports, frontends, contracts
```

## The generate cycle

Proto drives **API contracts**. When you change a `.proto` file:

```
{{.CLI}} generate
```

This rebuilds `gen/` (Go stubs, Connect handlers, TypeScript clients, mocks, middleware, bootstrap wiring), regenerates handler scaffolds and frontend hooks, and produces `forge_descriptor.json`.

It does **NOT** touch:
- `internal/db/` — entity types and ORM functions
- `db/migrations/` — database schema
- `handlers/<svc>/` — your business logic (existing files preserved)

## Contracts at every boundary

| Boundary | Defined by | Enforced by |
|----------|-----------|-------------|
| **External API** | Proto (`.proto` files) with `forge.v1` annotations | Generated Connect stubs |
| **Internal packages** | Go interfaces (`internal/<pkg>/contract.go`) | Compile-time type checking + contract linter |
| **Database schema** | SQL migrations (`db/migrations/`) | Postgres at runtime |

## Dev loop

```
{{.CLI}} run                  # Full stack: infra + Go (hot reload) + Next.js
{{.CLI}} test                 # Unit + integration tests
{{.CLI}} test e2e             # E2E tests (requires stack running)
{{.CLI}} lint                 # Go + proto + frontend linters
{{.CLI}} build                # Binaries + frontends + Docker images
{{.CLI}} deploy dev           # Deploy to local k3d cluster
```

## Key commands

| Command | When to use |
|---------|------------|
| `{{.CLI}} new <name>` | Create a new project |
| `{{.CLI}} add service <name>` | Add a new Connect RPC service |
| `{{.CLI}} add worker <name>` | Add a background worker |
| `{{.CLI}} add frontend <name>` | Add a Next.js frontend |
| `{{.CLI}} generate` | After any proto change — regenerates infrastructure |
| `{{.CLI}} db migration new <name>` | When you need to change the DB schema |
| `{{.CLI}} db migrate up --dsn $DSN` | Apply pending migrations |
| `{{.CLI}} run` | Start the full dev stack |
| `{{.CLI}} test` | Run tests |

